{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ESPJRwa2T651B9jppqkqij","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Node 1 is still showing as not live/available. This is frustrating. Let me check what's happening.\n\nThe node status is queried from crdb-cluster-0 itself, and it shows node 1 (itself) as not available. This is interesting - the node thinks it's not live.\n\nActually wait - when you run `cockroach node status` from a node, it queries the cluster's system tables. If the node's own liveness heartbeat keeps failing, it will show itself as not live.\n\nThe logs showed heartbeats taking 1-1.06s with err=<nil> (succeeding). \n\nI should check the status from node 2 to get another perspective. A node is considered live in CockroachDB if its liveness record updates within the liveness threshold—roughly 9 epochs at 1.5s each, so about 9 seconds. The pattern I'm seeing is the node toggling between live and dead as heartbeats succeed and then lag, which suggests the liveness window is tight and the heartbeat timing is right on the edge.\n\nLooking at that 18:03:44 log entry showing a 1-second heartbeat, that should easily fall within the 9-second window, so there's something else going on. The `is_live` flag might be calculated differently than just checking if the heartbeat succeeded—it could be that the liveness record in the system table is stale even though the heartbeat itself completed, possibly due to gossip propagation delays or a clock skew issue.\n\nThe epoch counter at 60 is telling—that's a lot of dead-to-alive transitions in just 14 minutes, suggesting the node has been flapping in and out of liveness. But the recent logs show successful heartbeats at 1.06s and 1.01s, which should mean the node is stable now. Yet the node status check 2 seconds later still shows it as not live, which points to a gossip propagation lag.\n\nWait, the readiness probe failures are the real clue here—94 failures means the node is consistently reporting as not ready when the `/health?ready=1` endpoint returns 503. A node only reports not-ready when it's actually unhealthy or unable to serve requests, so this isn't just a liveness gossip issue.\n\nThe pod started 14 minutes ago and has been struggling the entire time. I had the snapshot rebalance rate capped at 1 MiB, which would've severely throttled rebalancing, but I bumped it to 32 MiB about 6-7 minutes ago. Even with that increase, the node is still oscillating between live and not-live. I'm wondering if restarting the pod would help clear whatever's causing the persistent instability, or if there's something else preventing it from stabilizing.\n\nActually, looking at the recent logs more carefully, the node is successfully completing heartbeats now (no errors), but the node status still shows it as not live. This could mean the node status is displaying stale cached data. The issue might be that when I query from crdb-cluster-0, it's seeing its own liveness record as expired during the brief window between heartbeats. Let me try querying from a different node to get a clearer picture.\n\nI'm also wondering if there's a clock skew issue at play here. The node started at 17:49:44 and the status check is around 18:04:xx, with node status updates happening roughly every 20 seconds. Node 1's last update was at 18:04:39 showing is_available=false, which was only 6 seconds before the check. Let me wait a bit and check again to see if things stabilize, or maybe try restarting the pod to see if that helps reset the state.\n\nActually, I should consider whether the readiness probe failure is preventing the Kubernetes service from routing traffic to the node, which could be affecting how quickly the node receives heartbeat responses. Though that doesn't quite make sense since the liveness heartbeat is a direct Raft write to the liveness range, not going through the service load-balancer.\n\nLet me dig into what exactly triggers the \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" error. It happens when a node tries to write a liveness heartbeat but the Raft commit fails or times out, and by the time it retries, the other nodes have already incremented the epoch thinking this node is dead. So the real issue is slow Raft commits, which in a Kind cluster where all nodes share the same host disk means high I/O pressure from snapshot rebalancing is affecting all nodes simultaneously.\n\nThe other two nodes seem stable though, so maybe this is specific to crdb-cluster-0. I'm wondering if the node upgraded from v23.2 and needs data migration, but actually CockroachDB handles that at the cluster level when finalized, not per-node. Since the cluster has quorum with the other two nodes and the upgrade is done, the main problem is just node 0's liveness heartbeat failing. I should probably restart it to give it a fresh start, but first let me check the snapshot rebalance configuration to understand what's happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":478,"cache_read_input_tokens":56682,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":478},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"07fdbe37-a551-41f9-9d37-d7959767c867","uuid":"3840722f-2317-421c-ac43-85f3002bcd28","request_id":"req_011CcbnBaefqcWvF6KmA1nMv"}
