{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015C2FNmh5mwKSiPWpBjftE3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so kv.snapshot_rebalance.max_rate is still 32 MiB. The adversary hasn't changed it back.\n\nBut all 3 nodes are having liveness failures now. This is strange. Let me think...\n\nActually, I think what's happening is that the 11 remaining under-replicated ranges are in a situation where all 3 nodes are Raft leaders for some of these ranges (not just node 1). When node 1 was added back to the cluster, ranges started moving to rebalance. This created a lot of Raft activity across ALL nodes, not just node 1.\nWith the rebalance rate at 32 MiB, I'm probably seeing high I/O pressure simultaneously across all nodes. I could wait for rebalancing to finish, reduce the rate to something like 8 MiB to ease the I/O load, or investigate if another cluster setting is contributing to the problem. Looking at the heartbeat failures, nodes 2 and 3 are experiencing significant delays—node 2 took nearly 18 seconds and node 3 over 27 seconds—which suggests they're getting starved for resources.\n\nThe Raft commit lag of 17-27 seconds is alarming and points to something blocking commits from completing. I'm wondering if there's a limit on concurrent range snapshots that's causing bottlenecks, or if this is simply disk I/O saturation preventing the cluster from keeping up with the rebalancing workload.\n\nWith 3 nodes each pushing 32 MiB/s and 11 under-replicated ranges trying to replicate simultaneously, the shared disk in this Kind cluster could be getting hammered. I should try reducing the snapshot rebalance rate to something like 8 MiB/s to ease the pressure. But wait - the adversary might have deliberately cranked this setting up to something extreme like 512 MiB/s, and I reset it to the default 32 MiB. That's still causing problems, which suggests the real issue is the concurrent replication load itself, not 